    "slug": "pwas-for-african-markets",
    "title": "Progressive Web Apps: The Future of Web Development for African Markets",
    "excerpt": "How Progressive Web Apps (PWAs) are bridging the gap between websites and native apps for African users.",
    "content": "## What Are PWAs?\n\nProgressive Web Apps combine the best features of websites and native mobile applications. They load like regular web pages but offer app-like capabilities such as offline functionality, push notifications, and home screen installation. For European markets where data costs are high and device storage is limited, PWAs are a game-changer. They consume significantly less data than native apps and work reliably on 2G and 3G networks still common across the UK.\n\n## Why PWAs Work for UK Users\n\nData costs in the UK remain a barrier to app adoption. A typical native app might require 50-100MB to download, while a PWA is usually under 5MB. PWAs also work offline — crucial for users in areas with unreliable internet. Major UK brands like Amazon UK and Argos have adopted PWA technologies, with Argos reporting a 33% increase in conversions after implementing their PWA. Push notifications via PWAs achieve open rates of 25-30%, comparable to native apps.\n\n## Getting Started with PWAs\n\nConverting your existing website to a PWA involves adding a service worker, a web app manifest, and implementing HTTPS. Frameworks like Next.js and Angular have built-in PWA support. For London businesses targeting mobile users, a PWA can deliver native-like experience without the cost and complexity of developing separate iOS and Android apps. Boyzeth Solutions recommends PWAs for businesses where app-like engagement is needed but native app budgets are not feasible.",
