    "slug": "improving-roas-paid-advertising",
    "title": "Improving ROAS: Advanced Techniques for Paid Advertising in the UK",
    "excerpt": "Increase your return on ad spend with advanced optimization techniques tailored for UK campaigns.",
    "content": "## Understanding ROAS in the UK Context\n\nReturn on Ad Spend (ROAS) measures revenue generated for every Pound spent on advertising. A ROAS of 4:1 means you earn �4 for every �1 spent. While 4:1 is considered good globally, the target varies by industry in the UK. E-commerce businesses typically need 5:1 or higher due to thin margins, while service businesses can be profitable at 3:1.\n\n## Advanced Optimization Techniques\n\nImplement proper conversion tracking with offline conversion import. A London real estate agency might get leads online but close deals offline — without importing offline conversions, the algorithm cannot optimize for actual sales. Use value-based optimization where available — tell the algorithm to pursue high-value customers, not just any conversion. Test bid strategies — target CPA for cost control, target ROAS for revenue maximization. Layer in audience insights to discover new high-value segments.\n\n## Creative and Landing Page Optimization\n\nA/B test landing pages relentlessly. Sometimes the difference between 2:1 and 5:1 ROAS is a different headline or button color. Match your ad copy to your landing page message — the user's journey should feel seamless. Test different offers — free consultations, discounts, free shipping. Analyze the customer journey beyond the last click — use GA4's attribution models to understand which channels contribute to conversions at different stages. Improving ROAS is an ongoing process of testing, measuring, and refining.",
