    "slug": "website-security-best-practices-nigeria",
    "title": "Website Security Best Practices for UK Business Owners",
    "excerpt": "Protect your website and customer data with essential security practices for the UK online landscape.",
    "content": "## The Security Threat Landscape in the UK\n\nCybercrime is a growing concern in the UK, with businesses of all sizes being targeted. From phishing attacks to data breaches, the threats are real and costly. UK e-commerce sites and service platforms that handle customer data are particularly vulnerable. A security breach can damage your reputation, result in financial loss, and erode customer trust — which is hard to rebuild.\n\n## Essential Security Measures\n\nStart with the basics — use HTTPS with a valid SSL certificate. Keep your CMS, plugins, and server software updated — outdated software is the most common vulnerability. Use strong passwords and implement two-factor authentication for admin accounts. Regularly back up your website — store backups in a separate location. Install a web application firewall (WAF) and security plugin that monitors for suspicious activity.\n\n## Advanced Protection\n\nImplement CAPTCHA on forms to prevent spam and bot attacks. Use a content security policy (CSP) to prevent cross-site scripting. Conduct regular security audits and penetration testing. Educate your team about phishing and social engineering attacks. For e-commerce sites, ensure PCI DSS compliance if handling credit card information. Partner with a hosting provider that offers DDoS protection and regular security scans. Website security is an ongoing commitment, not a one-time setup. Regular vigilance protects both your business and your customers.",
