    "slug": "content-marketing-roi-measurement",
    "title": "Measuring Content Marketing ROI: A Framework for UK Brands",
    "excerpt": "Track and measure the return on investment of your content marketing efforts with practical frameworks.",
    "content": "## Why Content Marketing ROI is Tricky\n\nContent marketing is one of the hardest channels to measure accurately. Unlike paid advertising, where results are immediate and trackable, content marketing builds value over time. A blog post published today might generate leads six months from now. For UK businesses with limited marketing budgets, proving content marketing ROI is essential for securing continued investment.\n\n## What to Measure\n\nTrack a combination of metrics across the funnel. Top of funnel — page views, time on page, social shares. Middle of funnel — email signups, content downloads, lead magnet conversions. Bottom of funnel — content-assisted conversions, direct inquiries from blog readers, revenue attributed to content. Use Google Analytics to set up goals and track conversion paths. Assign value to different actions — a newsletter signup might be worth �500, a content download �2,000, and a direct conversion �50,000.\n\n## Calculating Your ROI\n\nTotal the cost of content creation (writer time, design, promotion) and divide by the revenue generated from content-attributed conversions. A simple formula: (Revenue from Content - Cost of Content) / Cost of Content x 100. For example, if you spent �300,000 on content in a quarter and generated �1,200,000 in attributed revenue, your ROI is 300%. Track this quarterly and compare against other channels. Content marketing typically has lower immediate ROI than paid ads but compounds over time — the content you create this year will generate returns for years to come.",
